[http://www.flickr.com/photos/23103743@N05]  @swanq -- Interesting tidbits from your link! <a href="http://www.winter-carnival.com/about_us/history/" rel="nofollow">Saint Paul Winter Carnival</a>:<blockquote>Attendance – The Saint Paul Winter Carnival attracts approximately 350,000 visitors a year.

Economic Impact – The Saint Paul Winter Carnival has an estimated $3.5 to $5 million in economic activity in the City of Saint Paul.</blockquote>
&nbsp;

While not the identical photo as above, a photo likely taken at the same time, a bit closer to the chute, appears in the <a href="http://memory.loc.gov/service/sgp/sgpnyt/1916/191602/19160213/0001.pdf" rel="nofollow">Picture Section</a> of the <i>New York Times</i> on February 13, 1916, with the following caption:<blockquote>
“SHOOTING THE CHUTES AT THE GREAT NORTHWEST OUTDOOR SPORTS CARNIVAL, ST. PAUL, MINN. The Capitol of Minnesota Can Be Seen in the Background and, on the Right, Indian Tepees for the Reception and Entertainment of the Participants. (<i>Photo from Underwood &amp; Underwood</i>)”</blockquote><i>&mdash;From The Library of Congress <a href="http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/about/index.html" rel="nofollow"><i>American Memory Collection</i></a>.</i>
